In this project, the research team aimed to develop a novel deep learning approach to enable efficient design and operations of future wireless networks with big data. Specifically, the project team, for the first time, leveraged the emerging deep learning techniques for spatiotemporal modeling and prediction in wireless networks by developing a new hybrid deep model, and showing its effectiveness and superiority with real data from a major wireless carrier. Moreover, they studied networking and system control problems from a whole new perspective by developing an experience-driven approach based on deep reinforcement learning, which enables a network or a protocol to learn the best way to control itself from its own experience (e.g., runtime statistics data), just like a human learns a skill (such as swimming and driving). To demonstrate this design philosophy, they focused on several fundamental networking problems, multi-path TCP congestion control, general traffic engineering, and scheduling in distributed data processing systems. Furthermore, they were the first to tackle the network reconfiguration problem using transfer learning in the context of experience-drive networking. To justify the effectiveness of these control framework, they conducted comprehensive experiments on a packet-level simulator and practical testbeds.

The research has produced 17 papers in premier conferences and journals. The PI and his students delivered presentations and invited talks at numerous conferences and universities. A total of 6 Ph.D. students were trained in this project, in which they learned theories and problem-solving skills. Moreover, they gained hands-on experience on simulation and software development with popular software and systems for deep learning and networking research.



